<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/bla_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Tournament Reports</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Tournament Reports</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/treports/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/heroclix/treports/treports.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/vs/treports/treports.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/lotr/treports/treports.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/treports/treports.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/bla_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Quantum Cards, Montreal, Quebec, Canada<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.92)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11045'>Patrick "Patrick M. S" Sullivan</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11045&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 10, 2003</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> Quantum Cards, Montreal, Quebec, Canada &#8211; Sunday, February 9th, 2003<br />
<br />
Fellowship Block Format<br />
<br />
Pre-Tourney Jank (feel free to fast forward...)<br />
<br />
So after spending the better part of the weekend visiting my gf&#8217;s folks, I was happy to get back to the city Sunday morning for my tournament at my favourite local card shop, Quantum Cards.  I arrive around noon but soon realise that the BadBeef brothers are still waiting for me to pick them up at the Subway station (whoops.). So back in the car, taxi over two world-class players back to the store and.... we&#8217;re ready to roll.<br />
<br />
We&#8217;re enough to be a sanctioned tournament (9 players) but we&#8217;re an odd number and I end up getting the first bye. This is good at it&#8217;ll give me the time to let you in on what I&#8217;m running today. Basically, it&#8217;s a modified BadBeef fellowship (card-drawing engine) allowing me to set up nasty Uruk-Hai hands for my opponent. Full props go to Mathieu Brochu for inspiring this type of deck and for designing the original version (of which I hear he did quite well with).  <br />
So the nine that showed up are:<br />
Me &#8211; Patrick Sullivan &#8211; 1941 &#8211; Modified BadBeef / Uruk beatdown<br />
Nick Tregmallia &#8211; 1557 &#8211; Archery/Nazgul (Nick had left the realm of LOTR a while ago and got back on the horse with the arrival of Two Towers. We&#8217;re all very happy he did)<br />
Patrick Malboeuf &#8211; 2103 &#8211; Moria Swarm / BadBeef<br />
David Malboeuf &#8211; 1873 &#8211; Uruk Beatdown / Horn<br />
Jonathan Verall &#8211; 1604 &#8211; no idea as to what he was playing. Whatever it was, it didn&#8217;t work... &#61514; <br />
Steven Judge &#8211; 1614 &#8211; Steve is my best LOTR casual play buddy in the world. He&#8217;s playing a deck I helped him design largely influenced by Alex Tennet&#8217;s pipeweed masterpiece.<br />
Ariadne MacGee &#8211; 1521 &#8211; She&#8217;s playing a Hobbit/Nazgul mix I helped her design (the Naz component is largely influenced by Tech Tactic&#8217;s Gandalf-Killer mix<br />
Olivier &#8211; 1500- GreyWizard/ Moria Swarm &#8211; Deck manipulation<br />
New guy (long-time player, first tournament experience) 1500 &#8211; Heavy pipeweed fellowship &#8211; this guy has been playing for a year, never been to a tournament before. Claims to have spent 3 thousand bucks on cards. Better keep two eyes on this guy (wish I could remember his gosh darnit name...)<br />
 <br />
So in the end, it&#8217;s very good that I got the bye because Olivier has never played the game before in his life! So he is playing against my friend, Nick Tregmallia and I&#8217;m judging the tournament along with Jonathan Verall and Patrick Malboeuf so I&#8217;m more than happy to sit it on their game and make sure that Olivier knows which phases are which and when (that and the fact that he doesn&#8217;t speak a word of English and Nick&#8217;s French is intermediate at best). So basically I&#8217;m like a U.N. translator inspecting this first match:<br />
<br />
<br />
Round One (ding ding)<br />
Nick Tregmallia (1557) Archery/Nazgul  <br />
Vs. <br />
Olivier (1500) Grey Wizard/Moria Swarm &#8211; deck manipulation<br />
Right away it seems like a super UN-fair match up. Nick&#8217;s much practised Mega archery fellowship vs. Olivier&#8217;s goblin-sneak deck manipulation shadow (a little too advanced for a beginner to be playing, IMHO). So, of course, Olivier continually forgets to use the Goblin Scavenger&#8217;s gametext as well as not using They Are Coming ever. Thus leaving Nick with a cakewalk to site 9. Worth noting, however, Olivier&#8217;s single-moving fellowship makes it to site 5 or 6 with only a couple casualties. He just kept playing skirmish events thereby avoiding being overwhelmed by Witch-King and Attea on numerous occasions. <br />
So Nick gets a FW, as do I for the bye.<br />
+3 / 3<br />
Highs: Getting to help a new guy learn the ropes in a sanctioned tournament<br />
	Olivier&#8217;s fellowship for surviving against a relentless Nazgul shadow<br />
Lows: Me getting the bye right off the bat thereby setting the stage for tragedy...<br />
<br />
Round Two<br />
Me &#8211; Patrick Sullivan (1941) modified BadBeef / Uruk beatdown<br />
Vs.<br />
David Malboeuf (1873) Horn/Uruk Beatdown<br />
The game that started off being the best of the day ended up becoming the worst experience so far in my career as a LOTR player. What had started off so good was that I had Dave convinced I was playing BadBeef/moria swarm with 4 copies of such a Little Thing. So he figured I was going to win no matter what. So he wins the bid and lets me go first. I get the best opening hand I&#8217;ve ever seen since Patrick Malboeuf&#8217;s opening hand in the Toronto Territorial finals against Josh (never forget that one). I pull out Thror&#8217;s Map, Sam, Galadriel, Elrond, Filbert, Bounder, Gimli, Aragorn and Rumil just for kicks. Holy cow. He was certain the game was over. So this is when he starts to play the most casual I&#8217;ve ever seen him play (meaning he&#8217;s not even pulling out his sites when I move because he just wants to get through the game, understandable). Here&#8217;s the funny thing, I am more nervous than I&#8217;ve been in a long time. I still can&#8217;t figure out why. So EVERY turn I forget to draw my card with the Grey Pilgrim. David and I are good friends so I ask him if I can draw my card during the fellowship phase, each time I ask he let me. Sure no problem. Nice guy. Dave and I are both members of Team Quantum as well as the newly formed Team CardShark so naturally, we allow each other takebacks, as all our games are quite casual.<br />
 So his shadow is actually giving my fellowship a hell of a beating. On every occasion where I should exert Sam or Aragorn to make them defender +1 or more, I forget and only remember after we settle archery actions. Once again, I ask Dave each time if I can go back to the Manuever phase and he says yes, no problem. So basically what happens next is I&#8217;m at site 7 and his fellowship has caught up to mine. Dave and I aren&#8217;t announcing cards as we play them, as this is a casual fun game and all. So his fellowship moves forward and I throw down 2 Saruman&#8217;s Ambitions. I put them along with the rest of my hobbit allies, elf allies, Thror&#8217;s map and other trinkets in my support area where they belong. What happens next is that Dave assigns Frodo to one of my Uruks knowing that I&#8217;m out of pumps in my hand. I end up using both Saruman&#8217;s ambitions to kill Boromir. Dave didn&#8217;t see that I had played the Saruman&#8217;s Ambitions so Boromir dies, by mistake and his fellowship quickly falls apart leading to Dave conceding the game at the next site. At this point, Dave is visibly upset by the turnout and quickly gathers his cards and goes outside for a smoke. At this moment, I assumed that David was upset because he lost a game he should have won. His brother Patrick stated that Dave would have won the game had he not lost Boromir at site 7. I&#8217;m still not so sure in that I had a ton of minions left including Tower Assassins in my hand and Saruman, Ravagers and others. But Patrick is a much better player than I am so I&#8217;ll take his word for it that Dave would have won the game had it not been for his mistake of assigning Boromir to a winless skirmish. <br />
I figured at this point, all was well until I stepped outside to check on Dave. This is when I got an earful.<br />
Basically to sum up, his point of view is that in a game where he allowed me more than a dozen takebacks, I should have offered him a takeback when he realised he made a game-losing mistake by not spotting the Ambitions. His argument is that it was a friendly casual game (as all our games are) and that this type of match should not be determined by an error. He is completely right, of course. Now for my side:<br />
I will always allow a take-back from a friend in a game (sanctioned or no). However, I have never once in my LOTR career OFFERED a take-back. I have always felt it is up to the person on whether or not he wants to request the take-back (which takes guts, by the way). If he doesn&#8217;t, then I naturally assume he has accepted his error and is willing to move on and live with it (I do this everytime I make a game-losing error, I&#8217;d much rather live with that mistake because I&#8217;m much less likely to repeat it when it counts). <br />
Anyway, Dave isn&#8217;t satisfied with my reasoning and goes back inside, leaving me out in the cold contemplating if I&#8217;ve jeopardised our friendship...<br />
FW +3 / 6<br />
Highs: None. It truly was the worst LOTR experience of my life.<br />
Lows: Gather the kids around, this is going to be long....<br />
	Basically the lows can be summed up in one sentence: <br />
	My play style and gaming ethic are damaging my valued friendships. <br />
	Before I begin, let me just say that the ending of this story is a happy one. Dave sent me a D-mail letting me know that we&#8217;re cool. Thank God. I don&#8217;t think I could have made it through another sleepless night.<br />
	This whole problem is nothing new to me. This is the third such instance that has happened to me involving three different CCG&#8217;s. Feel free to skip this whole section if you just want to get to the next round&#8217;s details. The first such instance was 10 years ago when I used to play Magic. I remembered becoming bored with the game so I built a &#8216;fun&#8217; deck that I entitled &#8216;walls and balls&#8217; All the creatures were walls that blocked the other players creatures from getting to me while all my spells were Fireballs and other direct-damage Red spells. It was EXTREMELY frustrating to play against. And do you guys remember when certain cards and strategies were called &#8216;cheap&#8217;? This was one of them. I like how LOTR doesn&#8217;t really have any cheap cards or strategies. I think the only one was Mirror decks but thank goodness those are gone. Anyway one evening (the last time I ever played Magic) I&#8217;m playing this deck against three of my friends in their basement. I got together with these guys twice a week to play. After I take out the first player for the umpteenth time, he gathers his cards, wishes the OTHER two guys a pleasant evening and walks out. This was my best friend for a couple years and I haven&#8217;t seen him since. Then (this is when things get good) I take out the second player with a few fireballs, he then gets up grabs my deck and throws it clear across the room! He then starts to get all physically threatening so I decide to leave and the next week give all my magic cards to my cousin, Alex (who is now playing LOTR, too).  Can you believe that? It&#8217;s just a card game and look at the damage my play style caused!<br />
Second instance, I&#8217;m playing SW: CCG. What a fun game, right? Well along comes the Montreal Territorial and I go with my friend Nick Tregmmalia (now playing LOTR as well) and I end up getting paired off with my best friend at the time (not Nick, another guy). It&#8217;s as close as a game gets and time runs out. I was playing VERY slow and he accuses me of stalling. Anyone that has played with me (even ask David Malboeuf) knows that I am a slow player (DecipherCon participants certainly remember me). But all of a sudden, when it counts, it certainly becomes convenient to accuse me of stalling when I&#8217;m playing at the speed I always play at. Anyway long story short, I get the timed win, he takes off and I don&#8217;t hear from him for almost a YEAR. That was also the last time I ever played Star Wars. I think I fed the cards to my friend Dan&#8217;s pet parakeet. He found the Vaporator&#8217;s to be especially tasty.<br />
So what is it with my play style? I mean, the problem is obviously me, right? No one could come across this much misfortune and be stupid enough to blame external factors. The funny thing with LOTR is, it&#8217;s the first of these games that I&#8217;m actually good at. And every non-friend I play (meaning first-time adversaries or anyone I don&#8217;t know well) always tells me that I&#8217;m a pleasure to play against and a true sportsman. So after a night of lying in bed thinking about this, I think the problem must be that I consider &#8216;casual play&#8217; to be something different than what my friend&#8217;s define it as. For me, casual play should still be by the rules (as in no proxies and legal card-size decks). I know my best play-testing buddy, Steve Judge agrees with this. We still allow each other takebacks but all our games we play are as if we&#8217;re in a sanctioned tournament (no proxies, sites are all displayed, no sloppiness). But other people would consider casual play to be VERY informal and the rules can be a little more lax. And you know what? I envy those people because they can have fun in that type of environment whereas it would drive my bananas. Like, I recently rated Blue Wizards deck &#8216;smallest deck ever&#8217; half a star because it was like 16 cards or something. But it was obviously only posted as a fun deck. It wasn&#8217;t a fluff post. The guy had seriously thought of a killer 16-card deck just for the fun of it. So what&#8217;s my fricking problem? I should have given him 5-stars just for the originality of it. <br />
Anyway I better shut-up now. I was worried that this game represented the beginning of the end of LOTR for me (as my CCG friend self-destruct circle has begun to spin.) but I think I`ll just fight it and not let the game get the better of me. I figure with guys like David who are obviously just trying to have fun, I should allow them all the take-backs they want (which I normally do anyway) but I won&#8217;t allow MYSELF to have a take-back. That way it&#8217;s always fair. That way I won&#8217;t defeat some friend and possibly damage our relationship because of one dumb game. I&#8217;ve said over and over how happy I was that Dominic Gaudreault eliminated me in Day three of DecipherCon because I would have felt terrible sending HIM home. Jesse Carlucci or Mike Long, not so much. <br />
Anyway sadly David isn&#8217;t coming to Vegas with Patrick and I. It looks like Team CardShark will consist of Patrick Malboeuf Mathieu Brochu and myself. I don&#8217;t think I&#8217;ve ever felt like such a lightweight before.<br />
Let&#8217;s hope I can get my act together before then and figure out a play-style where I&#8217;ll still earn the respect of my adversaries that don&#8217;t know me while maintaining a fun relaxed atmosphere when I play with my friends. Okay back to the tournament, I feel bad about ranting on like that. So in true Canadian fashion, I apologise for absolutely no reason.<br />
<br />
Round Three<br />
Me (1941) modified BadBeef / Uruk Beatdown<br />
Vs.<br />
Patrick Malboeuf (2103) &#8211; BadBeef/Moria Swarm<br />
Uh oh... Not only is Patrick all set to avenge his brother&#8217;s unfair loss but also I had a feeling Patrick might know a thing or two about my fellowship strategy (it&#8217;s named after him for God&#8217;s sake...). <br />
So he goes first and moves to Ettenmoors with Frodo and one or two other companions. I pull out a troop. Frodo blocks! So in an exertion battle to overwhelm Frodo, the ring-bearer ends up with 6 burdens but alive. Meanwhile, I&#8217;m hanging on to an Orthanc Beserker and an Uruk Captain. I&#8217;m pretty happy thinking I&#8217;ll get him by site 5. However, Patrick knows better than ANYONE else does that my BadBeef fellowship&#8217;s only weakness is Moria. So I doubled moved past him to get to site 3. And then I was the first to reach site 4 (thereby sacrificing my Hollin (STUPID ME)) So he gets a bunch of conditions down and some prankster must have yanked my Secret Sentinels because they&#8217;re no where to be seen. So I stop there, he moves to site 4 where I get some good stuff down and kill a companion or two. And then I move to the Bridge of Khazad-Dum. Remember in the movie when Frodo leaves the Depths of Moria and is all teary-eyes because he lost Gandalf. Well, my Frodo would have been far more traumatised. He plays a TON of Orcs along with the Balrog and a Sauron tracker just for a splash of colour. So I HAD 6 companions going into the skirmish phase. There are 3 Orcs on Frodo and he actually manages to survive! However, the ENTIRE rest of the fellowship perishes. So at this point I&#8217;m thankful to still be in the game and now realise I might be able to kill his fellowship with my Uruks when he moves to the Bridge... however... I&#8217;ve forgotten something. Now before you laugh, let me just say in my defence that I haven&#8217;t played Fellowship block for MONTHS (okay maybe not months but certainly almost a month). Anyway, turns out that the Balrog just happens to be fierce. I felt like quite a fool. So Frodo steps up to handle this demon of the underworld and holds up his.... Wait a sec. I haven&#8217;t drawn into either of my two Stings yet either? So Frodo steps up and says YOU CANNOT PASS! And The Balrog laughs and has a nice little after dinner-mint (then spits out the ring). <br />
FL +1 / 7.<br />
Highs: Patrick avenging his cheated brother. <br />
Lows:  Me forgetting the Balrog is a real pain. <br />
	Me for double moving against my fellowship&#8217;s only weakness.<br />
	Me for not knowing my fellowship&#8217;s only weakness.<br />
<br />
Round Four (FINAL ROUND!)<br />
Me (1941) Uruk Beatdown / modified BadBeef<br />
Vs.<br />
Nick Tregmmalia (1557) Nazgul / Archery<br />
This is the game that ended up being the most fun. But I could only think of Dave being pissed off at me the whole time so I didn&#8217;t enjoy the game as much as I would have normally. Last time I played Nick was at the Ottawa Territorial where my HUGE Aragorn / 9 walker fellowship walked right though his minions for an easy win. Turns out, Nick has learned a thing or two about the game. Actually let me say that all Quantum Cards players seemed to have learned a little something in the last while. I can remember the tournaments here being a lot easier. Patrick Malboeuf even said after the tournament that it wasn&#8217;t easy. Not in the least.<br />
Anyway Nick&#8217;s massive archery totals allowed him to get to site 4 very quickly whereas his Nazgul did a real nice job at stopping me at sites 2,3 and 4. So it looks like it&#8217;ll be up to my shadow. Luckily by single moving I was clogging his hand with Nazgul (twice I stung him and saw not 7 but 8 shadow cards). Anyway he fully healed up at site 6 but unfortunately the Anduin Wilderland took its toll on his fellowship. Frodo left the site exhausted and then, and only then, Filbert comes down. An exhausted Frodo can&#8217;t do much with that Filbert. So Site 9, Lurtz, Orthanc Beserker and two other Uruks come down without the help of Saruman to win the game.<br />
FW +3 /10<br />
Highs: Nick giving me a hell of a time with those pesky Nazgul<br />
	Man those Uruks are tough as nails<br />
Lows: Apparently my deck has a weakness to Nazgul as well as Moria. <br />
<br />
<br />
So that ends a very stress-filled tournament. Easily the worst one I&#8217;ve ever been to and that is entirely my fault. Everyone was in a super good mood including my friend Steve who had a lot of fun with his deck. I ended up placing 3rd overall. With David Malboeuf finishing 2nd and his brother, Patrick placing 1st. Wait a sec.... that means Team Quantum went 1-2-3 once again! Sweet!<br />
<br />
Props: <br />
	Nick for coming back to the game in good form<br />
	Steve for smiling all day<br />
	Ari for continually trying out new edibles for wound tokens. Too funny...<br />
	Jonathan for having a bad day<br />
	Jill for throwing a great tournament.<br />
	Patrick Malboeuf and Team Quantum in general for being the best in the biz!<br />
	David Malboeuf for writing me d-mail letting me know that everything is peachy between us.<br />
Slops:<br />
	David Malboeuf for writing me d-mail THE DAY AFTER the tournament thus leaving me with a whole night of wondering if I&#8217;ve lost my favourite wise-cracking LOTR player for good.<br />
<br />
	<br />
<br />
Hope you liked the TR. I think I&#8217;m getting a bit better with the game details.<br />
